AB  - The ongoing phenomenon of climate change, which is marked by rising temperatures and heavy rainfall, poses a significant threat to global food security. Although numerous studies have examined the nexus of climate change on food security, relatively few have explored this nexus in Southeast Asian (ASEAN). Using panel data from ten ASEAN countries between 1991 and 2023, this study makes three key contributions. First, it constructs a comprehensive food security index based on six dimensions. Second, it examines the relationship between temperature anomalies and food security, while accounting for cross-sectional dependencies, by employing a cross-sectionally augmented autoregressive distributed lag (CS-ARDL) approach. Third, it investigates the role of government quality in mitigating food insecurity across the ASEAN countries. The findings reveal that temperature anomalies significantly reduce food security in both the long- and short-run, positioning countries at a serious threat to achieving food security in the ASEAN region. Furthermore, government quality did not significantly mitigate the relationship between climate change and food security, suggesting limitations in governance capacity to address climate-related challenges. These findings suggest that stronger regional cooperation among ASEAN countries could help mitigate the impacts of climate change and promote sustainable and resilient food systems.
