TI  - Weather index insurance, agricultural productivity, and multiscale resilience. A comparative analysis of farmers with varying exposure to weather shocks in Kenya
T2  - JOURNAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT
LA  - English
KW  - Weather index insurance
KW  - Agricultural productivity
KW  - Shock intensity
KW  - Smallholder farmers
KW  - Climate resilience
KW  - Kenya
KW  - DEMAND
AB  - Smallholder agricultural productivity is crucial for global food security, yet it is vulnerable to yield volatility from weather shocks in rainfed systems. Financial and irrigation constraints limit conventional risk management, while market failures hinder traditional indemnity-based insurance. Weather Index Insurance (WII), which triggers payouts based on objective meteorological indices, is a potential solution. However, empirical evidence on the association between WII and agricultural productivity across varying shock intensities and social scales is limited, with many existing studies relying on controlled experiments that may not capture the complexity of real-world smallholder decision-making. This study addressed these gaps by analyzing observational data from 400 smallholder maize farmers in Kenya. We employed a linear regression model with village-level fixed effects to control for unobserved geographic heterogeneity. Shock severity was classified using farmer-reported yield loss as a proxy, with severe shocks defined as >40 % loss and mild/no shock as <= 40 % loss, a threshold aligned with the triggers in Kenyan WII programs. The model examined interaction effects between WII uptake, shock severity, and key agricultural inputs to explore the input intensification pathway. The results showed that the WII-yield association depended on shock severity and social scale. A positive association was observed under moderate shocks, but was not statistically significant during severe shocks, suggesting basis risk. This relationship was closely associated with input use, as the WII coefficient decreased upon the inclusion of modern inputs, supporting the input intensification pathway. Notably, a positive WII association persisted at the village level under severe stress, suggesting benefits from aggregate risk pooling. Input analysis revealed that improved seeds were consistently associated with higher yields across all scenarios, outperforming traditional varieties, while chemical fertilizers showed more pronounced benefits at the village level. Labor and pesticides were also positively associated with yield, with labor's association being strongest at the village level under severe shocks. We conclude that climate resilience in smallholder systems arises from the interaction of financial risk management, modern agricultural technologies, and supportive socio-institutional contexts. We recommend policies that prioritize bundled interventions combining meso-level insurance, reliable input access, and institutional strengthening to enhance climate resilience.
