AB  - Future risks of climate impact on the African continent due to socio-economic vulnerabilities and environmental degradation highlight the need for evidence-based adaptation options documented in the literature. Furthermore, the traditional reviewing approaches, such as narrative, systematic, and bibliometric, offer valuable insights into patterns of research productivity, emerging trends, and areas of potential impact of research papers published online. The bibliometric evaluations and topic modelling to systematically review the literature on climate adaptation strategies in Africa are considered in this paper using the Scopus database with 3,311 scholarly articles published between 1996 and 2024. Findings identified key characteristics of the research domain, including influential authors, institutions, and countries, as well as dominant themes and emerging trends within the field. Bibliometric analysis uncovered publication patterns and the contributions of various stakeholders to climate adaptation. The Structural Topic Modelling (STM) approach revealed the underlying semantic structures of the literature, highlighting principal research topics and knowledge gaps. The findings of this study indicated a predominance of research focusing on agricultural adaptation strategies, with notable underrepresentation of sectors such as health and urban planning. Therefore, it is suggested that policymakers and practitioners implement effective climate adaptation strategies tailored to the unique challenges faced in Africa.
