KW  - ISLAND
AB  - Climate change variability has severe impacts on various marine ecosystems. It imposes severe oceanographic changes, which are also responsible for more frequent and intense extreme weather events that threaten the livelihood of fishing communities. This study investigates climate change resilience and food security of smallscale fishing communities in Southeastern, Mindanao. Mainly, to document climate change impacts to coastal fishing communities as well as assess their food security in the region. To do these, two methods were applied: semi-structured questionnaires, and focus group discussions (FGDs). The climate resilience of the communities was investigated using a selection of 12 indicators adapted for this study. Food consumption score (FCS) was used to grasp communities' food security. Four municipalities (Mabini, Lupon, San Isidro, and Mati) were studied, with N = 403 respondents for the semi-structured questionnaires and N = 168 participants for the focus groups. San Isidro had the highest percentage of resilient respondents while Mabini presented with the highest percentage of food secure respondents. Overall, climate resilience appeared to be correlated only with age and experience of fishers. However, the focus groups revealed a different reality regarding food security. Our results corroborate the limitations of the FCS method that have been previously highlighted by other authors. This paper exposed several challenges that these communities are facing and can be used as a baseline to improve their wellbeing, increase their resilience and empower them through other livelihood opportunities.
