AB  - This study examines the spatio-temporal patterns of agricultural drought and farmers' perceptions in the Eastern Province of Rwanda from 2001 to 2020, using the Vegetation Health Index (VHI) derived from remote sensing data alongside surveys of 350 farmers to explore perceptions of climate change and adaptation strategies. VHI analysis reveals significant inter-annual variability, with major drought events occurring in 2003-2006 and 2015-2017, and healthier vegetation during 2001-2002, 2007-2008, and 2012-2014. Peak drought years (2004, 2009, 2016, and 2019) affected more than 10% of the region. Survey results indicate a predominantly male farming population (80.86%), with most respondents having primary or secondary education. A substantial majority (67.71%) acknowledged climate change, reporting decreased and shifted rainfall patterns, and identifying drought as the principal threat to crop yields and livestock. Farmers employ a suite of drought-mitigation strategies, with water harvesting, crop diversification, and the use of drought-resistant varieties contributing to resilience. Adoption of irrigation, zero grazing, and early warning systems varies across districts; predominantly manual irrigation methods (82.29%) are common, and limited access to advanced technologies is driven by financial constraints and knowledge gaps. While numerous mitigation measures were provided by the government, farmers expressed low satisfaction. The findings underscore the need for enhanced financial support, improved infrastructure, tailored district-level assistance, expanded access to resources, and strengthened information sharing to build drought resilience and promote sustainable agriculture.
